bib.title: Hot Fusion-Evaporation Cross Sections Of 45Sc-Inducedreactions With Lanthanide Targets

free_txt: Towson University, Towson, Maryland
Experiments were performed at the
Cyclotron Institute at Texas A&M University using the
K500 superconducting cyclotron.
Compiled by S.H.
The Momentum Achromat Recoil Spectrometer (MARS)
was used to momentum analyze the reaction products and
suppress the beam particles in spectrometer focal
plane. The desired reaction products were tuned through
MARS by estimating the most probable charge state.
Reaction products that reached the detector
chamber implanted into a 50mm x 50mm Micron model X1
position-sensitive silicon detector with 16
position-sensitive vertical strips and a full-energy
signal.
Alpha decays were discriminated from
implantation events via a large-area microchannel
plate (MCP) detector. Incoming ions passed through a
0.6 mu-m Al foil and ejected secondary electrons,
which were steered onto the plates of the MCP by an
electrostatic grid. Coincident signals in the SISD
and MCP indicated a recoil event, while a signal only
in the SISD indicated alpha decays.

Experiments were performed at the
Cyclotron Institute at Texas A&M University using the
K500 superconducting cyclotron.
Beams of 45Sc6+ were delivered from the K500 cyclotron
with intensities on-target of 0.5 - 8.0 pnA.
Coincidence between position sensitive Si
detector and microchannel plate detector indicated
recoil event. Reaction products were identified by
characteristic alpha decay energies. Decay events
were characteristic solely by Si detector signal.
Reaction products were implanted in Si strip
detector and identified according to energy of alpha
particle from compound nucleus decay
